---
layout: article
title: Storage
description: Upload and serve files with Appwrite Storage. Use buckets and permissions for access control, file tokens for temporary download links, and built-in image transforms so you can skip running a separate image service for common cases.
back: /docs
---

Appwrite **Storage** fits files your users or servers create: profile photos, attachments, PDFs, video, or static bundles. If it is binary and too large to live in a database row, it probably belongs here.

Files go into [buckets](/docs/products/storage/buckets). You set [permissions](/docs/products/storage/permissions) on the bucket so only the right people or roles can read or write. For private files, create a short [file token](/docs/products/storage/file-tokens) when someone should download or preview - instead of sharing a permanent link.

For images, [image transformations](/docs/products/storage/images) let you crop, resize, or change format from the URL. [Upload and download](/docs/products/storage/upload-download) covers the usual flows, including larger files. Keep titles, ownership, and business fields in [Databases](/docs/products/databases); Storage holds the bytes.

{% info title="Looking for a database?" %}
Storage is for blobs and files. For structured records such as profiles, orders, or posts, use [Appwrite Databases](/docs/products/databases).
{% /info %}

