# Core concepts {% #core-concepts %}

Buckets, permissions, tokens, and file APIs are the main pieces to configure before you wire Storage into your app.

{% cards %}
{% cards_item href="/docs/products/storage/buckets" title="Buckets" %}
Group files by use case, region, or access pattern with per-bucket settings.
{% /cards_item %}
{% cards_item href="/docs/products/storage/permissions" title="Permissions" %}
Decide who can read, create, update, or delete objects at the bucket level.
{% /cards_item %}
{% cards_item href="/docs/products/storage/file-tokens" title="File tokens" %}
Issue scoped, expiring URLs for private downloads and previews.
{% /cards_item %}
{% cards_item href="/docs/products/storage/upload-download" title="Upload and download" %}
Stream large objects, handle resumable flows, and integrate with your backends.
{% /cards_item %}
{% cards_item href="/docs/products/storage/images" title="Image transformations" %}
Resize, crop, compress, and format images on demand via URL parameters.
{% /cards_item %}
{% /cards %}

# When to use Storage {% #when-to-use-storage %}

Use Storage when you mainly need to **store and deliver files**, not join them like database rows. Put the facts about each file (who owns it, what it is for) in [Databases](/docs/products/databases), and use [Functions](/docs/products/functions) if you need to generate files or react to uploads with custom logic.

Common examples: user avatars and galleries, invoices or exports users download, and shared media used on web and mobile with the same access rules.
